# Supabase Auth Database Sync

## Background and Motivation
The app can successfully sign-up users and these users appear in the **Auth ‚Üí Users** section of the Supabase dashboard.
However, when looking at **Database ‚Üí Tables**, the user cannot see any schema or table that relates to these accounts.
This is confusing and blocks any future work that requires a user-profile table (e.g., storing display names, avatars, roles, etc.).

Supabase automatically stores authentication records in the `auth` schema, while the **Database** screen defaults to the `public` schema.
We need to (a) verify that the default `auth` tables are present, (b) decide what additional tables we want (usually a `profiles` table in `public`), and (c) create them via migration so they show up in the dashboard and can be queried from the app.

## Key Challenges and Analysis
* New Supabase users often overlook that the **auth** schema is separate from **public**.
* The dashboard UI hides other schemas unless explicitly selected.
* We must design the extra user-profile table: minimal fields, FK to `auth.users`, RLS policy.
* Ensure migrations are idempotent and committed to source control.
* Coordinate Expo (React Native) client to upsert profile data after sign-up.

## High-level Task Breakdown
- [ ] **T1 ‚Äì Verify existing `auth` schema**
  ‚Ä¢ Open Supabase ‚Üí Database ‚Üí **auth** schema and confirm `users`, `refresh_tokens`, etc. exist.
  ‚Ä¢ Success = `auth.users` table visible.
- [x] **T2 ‚Äì Clarify required user-profile fields**
  ‚Ä¢ Based on the schema draft, we'll use the `users` table design from line 144.
  ‚Ä¢ Fields: id (UUID, PK, refs auth.users), school_id, email, full_name, phone, role (user_role enum), avatar_url, teacher_id, parent_id, student_id, is_active, last_login_at, invited_by, invited_at, activated_at, created_at, updated_at.
  ‚Ä¢ Success = Fields confirmed from schema draft.
- [x] **T3 ‚Äì Create migration for `public.users` table**
  ‚Ä¢ Created tables: `schools`, `users` (profile table), and `user_role` enum type.
  ‚Ä¢ Enabled RLS with policies for users to manage their own profiles and admins to manage school users.
  ‚Ä¢ Success = Tables appear under `public`, migrations applied.
- [x] **T4 ‚Äì Seed/Back-fill existing users into `users` table**
  ‚Ä¢ Created migration to insert rows for all existing auth users.
  ‚Ä¢ Added trigger to automatically create profile for new signups.
  ‚Ä¢ Success = All auth users have corresponding entries in the `public.users` table.
- [x] **T5 ‚Äì Update client code to upsert profile after registration / sign-in**
  ‚Ä¢ Updated the `signUp` function in `authStore.ts` to call `loadUserProfile()` after successful registration.
  ‚Ä¢ This ensures the client loads the profile created by our database trigger.
  ‚Ä¢ Success = Client code now properly handles profile loading after registration.
- [x] **T6 ‚Äì Smoke test end-to-end**
  ‚Ä¢ Verified existing users in `auth.users` have corresponding entries in `public.users`.
  ‚Ä¢ Confirmed RLS policies are correctly applied to the `users` table.
  ‚Ä¢ Success = Both tables populated, RLS enforced.
- [x] **T7 ‚Äì Documentation & Lessons Learned**
  ‚Ä¢ Updated `docs/LESSONS_LEARNED.md` with detailed information about Supabase auth schema and user profiles.
  ‚Ä¢ Added best practices for implementing user profiles with Supabase auth.
  ‚Ä¢ Success = Documentation updated for future reference.

